Present: Describes actions or states happening now, or general truths.
Past: Describes actions or states that happened before now.
Future: Describes actions or states that will happen after now.
Non-past (Present/Future): A single form used for both present and future time, interpreted by context.
Preterite (Simple Past): Describes a completed past action, often as a single whole event.
Imperfect: Describes ongoing, habitual, repeated, or background actions in the past.
Present Progressive (Continuous): Describes an action currently in progress.
Past Progressive (Continuous): Describes an action that was in progress at a specific past time.
Future Progressive (Continuous): Describes an action that will be in progress at a specific future time.
Present Perfect: Links a past action to the present, emphasizing current relevance or result.
Past Perfect (Pluperfect): Describes an action completed before another past event.
Future Perfect: Describes an action that will be completed before a specific future time.
Present Perfect Progressive (Continuous): Emphasizes duration of an activity that started in the past and continues to now (or just ended with present effect).
Past Perfect Progressive (Continuous): Emphasizes duration of an activity that was ongoing before another past event.
Future Perfect Progressive (Continuous): Emphasizes duration of an activity up to a specific point in the future.
Conditional (Simple): Describes what would happen under certain conditions.
Conditional Perfect: Describes what would have happened under certain past conditions.
Habitual Past: Describes actions that occurred regularly or repeatedly in the past.
